<TITLE> US orders first 16,000 deployments of Afghan surge </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dec, 8 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The US Defense Department has announced the deployment of the first 16,000 of the 30,000 additional troops being sent into Afghanistan. Following are details provided by the Pentagon on the timing and structure of those forces, the vast majority of which will not arrive until the spring: 1,500 MARINES ARRIVE IN DECEMBER An infantry battalion task force, with about 1,500 Marines, will deploy later this month from Camp Lejeune in North Carolina. The Marines are mainly expected to be deployed in southern Afghanistan, where fighting has been the heaviest, but the Pentagon did not say where the initial forces were headed. NEXT 7,000 MARINES IN SPRING Another 6,200 Marines from Regimental Combat Team-2, headquartered at Camp Lejeune, will deploy to Afghanistan in the early spring. Another 800 Marines from I Marine Expeditionary Force at Camp Pendleton in California will deploy later in the spring. ARMY SENDS TRAINERS The Army will send a Brigade Combat Team with 3,400 soldiers, on a training mission in the early spring. The soldiers will come from the 1st Brigade, 10th Mountain Division at Fort Drum in New York. ENABLERS DEPLOYING Defense Secretary Robert Gates also approved the deployment of approximately 4,100 support forces, which will deploy at various times into spring 2010. These forces provide essential services to US troops and are expected to include medics, surveillance experts and land mine clearance teams. REST OF THE TROOPS BY THE FALL The Pentagon has said that about 20,000 to 25,000 troops will be deployed by July and all of the 30,000 forces by the fall but no additional deployments were announced on Tues
